  "output": "## Scope note\n\nThis directory (`apps/cli`) is a **Go TUI app** (Bubble Tea) that shells out to a Python crawler per provider — there's no database and no React here (that's `apps/crawler` and possibly a web app elsewhere, which I don't have access to from this session). So \"N+1 queries\" and \"React re-renders\" don't literally apply; I've translated the same categories into their real Go/TUI equivalents. The whole codebase is 2 files (~480 lines), so this is a complete review, not a sample.\n\n## 1. Redundant computation — `articlesSaved()` rescans full log history every render\n\n`tui.go:398` calls `articlesSaved(st.lines)` for **every provider, on every `View()` call** — and `View()` runs on every `tea.Msg`, including the spinner tick (fires every ~100ms by default) while any provider is running.\n\n```go\n// tui.go:360-368 — O(n) scan...\nfunc articlesSaved(lines []string) int {\n\tn := 0\n\tfor _, l := range lines {\n\t\tif strings.HasPrefix(l, \"  - \") {\n\t\t\tn++\n\t\t}\n\t}\n\treturn n\n}\n// ...called for every provider on every render — tui.go:398\ncount := articlesSaved(st.lines)\n```\n\nAs a crawl runs longer, each provider's `lines` slice grows, and you're redoing the full scan ~10x/second × N providers. This is the CLI-equivalent of \"N+1\" — repeated full re-derivation of something that should be incrementally maintained.\n\n**Fix:** maintain a running counter, updated once per line as it arrives.\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate      providerState\n\tlines      []string\n\tsavedCount int // maintained incrementally instead of rescanned\n}\n\n// in Update(), statusMsg case (tui.go:107-114)\ncase statusMsg:\n\tst := m.statuses[msg.provider]\n\tst.state = stateRunning\n\tst.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)\n\tif strings.HasPrefix(msg.line, \"  - \") {\n\t\tst.savedCount++\n\t}\n\t...\n\n// viewRunning (tui.go:398)\ncount := st.savedCount\n```\n\n## 2. O(n²) rebuild — `refreshViewport` re-joins the entire log on every single line\n\n```go\n// tui.go:245-252\nfunc (m *model) refreshViewport() {\n\tname := m.highlighted()\n\tif name == \"\" {\n\t\treturn\n\t}\n\tm.vp.SetContent(strings.Join(m.statuses[name].lines, \"\\n\"))\n\tm.vp.GotoBottom()\n}\n```\n\nThis is called from the `statusMsg` handler (`tui.go:111-113`) **every time a single new line arrives** for the highlighted provider. `strings.Join` walks the *entire* accumulated slice each time, so total work across a run with `n` lines is O(n²). With `--limit 0` (\"run until exhausted\"), a chatty provider can emit thousands of lines, and this gets visibly slower as it goes.\n\n**Fix:** accumulate into a `strings.Builder` (O(1) amortized append) instead of joining from scratch:\n\n```go\ntype providerStatus struct {\n\tstate   providerState\n\tlines   []string\n\tcontent strings.Builder // append-only, avoids re-joining on every line\n}\n\n// on new line:\nif st.content.Len() > 0 {\n\tst.content.WriteByte('\\n')\n}\nst.content.WriteString(msg.line)\n\n// refreshViewport:\nm.vp.SetContent(st.content.String())\n```\n\n(`viewport.SetContent` still needs a full string per Bubble Tea's API, but you eliminate the repeated join — the expensive part.)\n\n## 3. Unbounded memory growth — no cap on retained log lines\n\n`st.lines`/`st.content` grow forever for the lifetime of a run, for **every** provider (not just the highlighted one), even though only the highlighted provider's content is ever displayed. For a long unlimited (`--limit 0`) multi-provider crawl this can hold a large amount of text in memory simultaneously.\n\n**Fix:** if you need the full history for anything beyond the display + count, keep it; otherwise cap the retained/displayed lines with a ring buffer and keep `savedCount` (fix #1) as the separate, cheap source of truth for the count:\n\n```go\nconst maxRetainedLines = 2000\n\nst.lines = append(st.lines, msg.line)\nif len(st.lines) > maxRetainedLines {\n\tst.lines = st.lines[len(st.lines)-maxRetainedLines:]\n}\n```\n\n## 4. Leak-adjacent: child processes have no cancellation, and scan errors are swallowed\n\n```go\n// main.go:59-78\nfunc runCrawler(name string, limit int, crawlerDir string, onLine func(string)) error {\n\tcmd := exec.Command(\"uv\", \"run\", \"main.py\", name, \"--limit\", fmt.Sprint(limit))\n\t...\n\tscanner := bufio.NewScanner(stdout)\n\tfor scanner.Scan() {\n\t\tonLine(scanner.Text())\n\t}\n\treturn cmd.Wait()\n}\n```\n\nTwo issues here:\n\n- **No cancellation path.** `exec.Command` (not `exec.CommandContext`) means there's no way to kill the `uv run main.py` subprocess if the TUI exits abnormally (crash, `SIGKILL`, terminal closed). Orphaned Python crawler processes can keep running. This is compounded by the fact that `q`/`ctrl+c` are actively *ignored* while any provider is running (`tui.go:146-150`), so the only way out mid-run is to kill the whole process tree externally.\n- **`scanner.Err()` is never checked.** `bufio.Scanner` has a default 64KB max token size; if a single line from the Python crawler ever exceeds that, `Scan()` returns `false` silently, the loop exits early, and the rest of that provider's output is dropped with no error surfaced.\n\n**Fix:**\n\n```go\nfunc runCrawler(ctx context.Context, name string, limit int, crawlerDir string, onLine func(string)) error {\n\tcmd := exec.CommandContext(ctx, \"uv\", \"run\", \"main.py\", name, \"--limit\", fmt.Sprint(limit))\n\t...\n\tfor scanner.Scan() {\n\t\tonLine(scanner.Text())\n\t}\n\tif err := scanner.Err(); err != nil {\n\t\treturn fmt.Errorf(\"scan output: %w\", err)\n\t}\n\treturn cmd.Wait()\n}\n```\n\nDerive `ctx` from `signal.NotifyContext(context.Background(), os.Interrupt)` in `main()` and pass it down through `startRun`/`runHeadless`, so a genuine interrupt actually tears down the subprocess tree.\n\n## Not applicable here (for completeness)\n\n- **N+1 queries / caching layer**: no DB/API client in this file set — that logic lives in `apps/crawler` (Python), which is outside this session's allowed directory (`apps/cli` only). If you want that reviewed too, point me at it directly.\n- **React re-renders**: no React in this app; the closest analogue is the `View()` rescans covered in #1/#2 above.\n\n**Priority if you want me to implement:** #1 and #2 are the real wins (cheap, isolated, fix the actual growth-rate problem) — happy to make those edits now if you'd like.\n",
